With that said, all stocks have a certain personality, and based on that you need to learn how to trade it. $AMD is one of the most schizophrenic, so I never hold very long and will sell even at minor resistances or when a turn looks like it's coming.

I'm fast to take profits when a stock is in an uncomfortable price range, which $AMD was. I'll try to find a stock I'm more comfortable with using the money after the sell. For me it isn't about big wins it's about consistent profit. If I'm uncomfortable in a position, I sell.

This strategy has also saved me many times as $AMD fell hard. My net gain is likely much higher than a single big play because of this cautious trading. It's not flashy but works. In my opinion it's never a mistake to take profit, even though the "what could have been" can sting.

Today my primary mistake was selling $AMD too early, but was it really a mistake? As a heavy $AMD trader I know how iffy it can be to trade so I usually sell it quickly. This has caused me to miss big $AMD moves, but I'm still very profitable on it by trading small fluctuations
